  "prompt": "How is mass and weight related?",
  "response": "Mass and weight are related, but they are not the same thing:\n\n1. Mass:\n- Mass is a measure of the amount of matter in an object\n- It is constant regardless of location\n- Measured in kilograms (kg)\n- Does not change with gravity\n\n2. Weight:\n- Weight is the force of gravity acting on an object's mass\n- Changes depending on gravitational field strength\n- Measured in Newtons (N)\n- Varies with location (e.g., less on the moon, more on Earth)\n\nRelationship:\n- Weight = Mass \u00d7 Gravitational acceleration\n- On Earth, weight = mass \u00d7 9.8 m/s\u00b2\n- Example: A 10 kg object on Earth weighs 98 Newtons\n\nKey differences:\n- Mass is intrinsic to an object\n- Weight depends on gravitational field\n- An object's mass remains the same everywhere, but its weight changes\n\nSimple analogy:\n- Mass is like the amount of \"stuff\" in an object\n- Weight is how much that \"stuff\" is pulled down by gravity",
